  "content": {
    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three cases, labeled A, B, and C, of a block of mass m moving to the right along a horizontal surface and colliding with another block of mass m that is at rest. Case A shows the moving block coming to rest after the collision and the other block moving to the right. Case B shows the two blocks moving to the right together after the collision. Case C shows the stationary block remaining at rest after the collision while the moving block bounces back to the left, opposite to its initial direction of movement.\" src=\"/images/4181200f20bd4c696f4b410c01b08146.svg\"></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">In each of three different collisions cases, two blocks of the same mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\"><math alttext=\"m\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>m</mi></math></span></span> can move on a horizontal surface with negligible friction, as shown in the figure. In each collision, one block is initially moving to the right along the surface and then collides with the second block, which is initially at rest. In case <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>A</mtext></math></span></span>, the moving block comes to rest after the collision. In case <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span>, the two blocks move together after the collision. In case <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>C</mtext></math></span></span>, the stationary block is fixed in place on the surface and remains at rest after the collision, and the moving block changes direction but has the same speed before and after the collision. Which of the following correctly compares the changes in kinetic energy <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta K sub A\"><math alttext=\"delta K sub A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mtext>Δ</mtext><msub><mi>K</mi><mtext>A</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta K sub B\"><math alttext=\"delta K sub B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mtext>Δ</mtext><msub><mi>K</mi><mtext>B</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta K sub C\"><math alttext=\"delta K sub C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mtext>Δ</mtext><msub><mi>K</mi><mtext>C</mtext></msub></mstyle></math></span></span> of the two-block systems in cases <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>A</mtext></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>B</mtext></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>C</mtext></math></span></span>, respectively?</p>\n",
